\begin{definition}
Given a particle $\Omega(t_{1},t_{2},\ldots,t_{n})$, the ascending order of
its chromatic components is called the \emph{chromatic base} of the particle,
and denoted by $\beta(\Omega)=\{t_{1}^{\prime},t_{2}^{\prime},\ldots
t_{n}^{\prime}\}$.
\end{definition}

For example, cells $\zeta_{1}(0,2,3,1)$ and $\zeta_{2}(2,1,3,0)$ both have the
same base $\beta(\zeta_{1})=\beta(\zeta_{2})=\{0,1,2,3\}$. If two components
are equal, their orders are in random. For example, the base of edges
$(\frac{3}{2},0,3,\frac{3}{2})$ and $(\frac{3}{2},\frac{3}{2},3,0)$ are both
$\{0,\frac{3}{2},\frac{3}{2},3\}$. Chromatic codes are actually the
permutations of different bases. In previous studies, chromatic base was also
called the primary code of a cell \cite{Zhu2010}.


